  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 7, 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The two accordingly go ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "by night",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or \"at night,\" as soon as night came on, and find Saul asleep ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "within the trench,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " inside the wagon rampart, as in ver. 5, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "his spear,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the sign of his royal authority, stuck in the ground; not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "at his bolster,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " but \"at his head; and so in vers. 11, 12, 16. The word literally signifies \"the place where the head is.\" Like David's men in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 24:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Abishai sees in Saul's defenceless condition a proof that it was God's will that he should die, but there is a difference of language in the Hebrew which the A.V. does not represent. There the word rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "deliver",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is really ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "give",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; here it is \"hath locked up.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "At once.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Hebrew, \"once.\" Abishai would pierce him through with a single stroke so thoroughly that no second blow would be necessary. The purpose of this would be to prevent an outcry. 1 Samuel 26:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Upon the receipt of this information, David rose up with two attendants (mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 26:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to reconnoitre the camp of Saul. When he saw the place where Saul and his general Abner were lying - Saul was lying by the waggon rampart, and the fighting men were encamped round about him - he said to Ahimelech and Abishai, \"Who will go down with me into the camp to Saul?\" Whereupon Abishai declared himself ready to do so; and they both went by night, and found Saul sleeping with all the people. Ahimelech the Hittite is never mentioned again; but Abishai the son of Zeruiah, David's sister (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and a brother of Joab, was afterwards a celebrated general of David, as was also his brother Joab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 16:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 18:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Saul's spear was pressed (stuck) into the ground at his head, as a sign that the king was sleeping there, for the spear served Saul as a sceptre (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 18:10",
        "children": []
      },
